    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/44a24c06d5a7f17e8c673b0ccefd6445?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 4830178,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3898555,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3898555/jaysee",
                "reputation": 466,
                "display_name": "jaysee"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1490338611,
            "creation_date": 1490253170,
            "body": "<p>You could add a method annotated with @PrePersist or @PreUpdate to your entity to clean up your data. This method will be called automatically before every insert or update.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>import javax.persistence.Entity;\nimport javax.persistence.PrePersist;\nimport javax.persistence.PreUpdate;\n\n@Entity\npublic class MyEntity{\n\n   @PrePersist\n   @PreUpdate\n   private void cleanup() {\n       ...correct your data here...\n   }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 42969443,
            "question_id": 42966113,
            "last_edit_date": 1490338611
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/HZplG.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 6766059,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 5211043,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5211043/the-bitman",
                "reputation": 1339,
                "display_name": "The Bitman",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1490264959,
            "creation_date": 1490264959,
            "body": "<p>This is not the responsibility of the dao/domain layer to validate the data, rather the presentation and/or business layers. So check the data at the client or one of the controllers from the business layer and just call the domain layer with validated data (or throw an EInvalidXXXX exception)<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 42973412,
            "question_id": 42966113
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/bXJXD.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 8277997,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 6223518,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6223518/dave-pateral",
                "reputation": 1465,
                "display_name": "Dave Pateral",
                "accept_rate": 58
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1490237538,
            "creation_date": 1490237538,
            "body": "<p>You don't need to handle this logic in your code, <code>hibernate<\/code> can do this for you. Set <code>hbm2ddl.auto<\/code> property to <code>create<\/code> in <code>hibernate.cfg.xml<\/code>, hibernate will drop the existing table and create a new one every time you run the application. If you don't want to create a new table anymore, set the property to <code>update<\/code>, hibernate will append data on the table.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;property name=\"hbm2ddl.auto\"&gt;create&lt;/property&gt;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 42966383,
            "question_id": 42966113
        }
